<section>
<title>Answers</title>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-Toprepareforclass36">
  <title>To prepare for class</title>

      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            1250 square feet
          </p>

          <p>
            Our goal is to maximize <m>A(x,y) = xy</m> where <m>x</m> represents the length of two sides of fence and <m>y</m> is the length of the other (the length parallel to the wall being used).
            We maximize <m>A(x,y)</m> subject to the condition that <m>2x+y=100</m>.
            By solving for <m>y</m>, we aim to maximize
            <me>
              A(x)=x(100-2x) = 100x-2x^{2}
            </me>
            on the domain <m>0 \leq x \leq 50</m> (because <m>0 \leq y=100-2x \leq 100</m>).
            Since <m>A'(x) = 100-4x</m> we find a critical value at <m>x=25</m> that leads to a global maximum of <m>A</m> on its domain.
            <m>A(25) = 1250</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The positive number is <m>\sqrt{2}</m>.
            The function <m>Q(x)</m> being minimized is <m>Q(x) = x + \frac{2}{x}</m>.
            It is being minimized on the domain <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
            Since <m>Q'(x) = 1-2x^{-2}= 1-\frac{2}{x^{2}}= 0</m> exactly when <m>x=\pm \sqrt{2}</m>, we see that <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is the only critical point in the domain.
            A first derivative sign chart shows us that this is a local minimum.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            We maximize
            <me>
              A(x) = \frac{1}{2}x(2x) \cdot \left[ \frac{1}{2}(1)(2) - \frac{1}{2}x(2x)\right] = x^{2} [1-x^{2}]
            </me>
            on the interval <m>0 \leq x \leq 1</m>.
            Note that
         <md><mrow> A'(x) = \mathstrut \amp 2x(1-x^2) + x^2(-2x)</mrow>
          <mrow>  = \mathstrut \amp x[ 2(1-x^2) + x(-2x)]</mrow>
          <mrow>  = \mathstrut \amp x [2-4x^2].</mrow></md>
            It follows that <m>A'(x)=0</m> exactly when <m>x=0</m> or <m>\displaystyle x=\pm \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m>.
            A first derivative sign chart appears in <xref ref="figurefirstderivativesignchart36"/>.
          </p>
          
<figure xml:id="figurefirstderivativesignchart36">
  <image xml:id="firstderivativesignchart36Pic" width="75%">
<description>
A number line labeled A′(x). Three marked x-values appear: 0, the square root of 2 divided by 2, and 1. A plus sign above the left interval indicates A′(x) is positive there, a minus sign above the middle interval indicates A′(x) is negative, and a plus sign above the right interval indicates A′(x) is positive again.
</description>
